{
  "doc_id": "26908",
  "text": "Permafrost and the associated soils cover more than 25 % of the land surface [CITATION_1] . These ecosystems play an essential role for the Earth's climate due to the large amount of organic carbon preserved in the soils and sediments [CITATION_2] ) and because of the rapidly warming of permafrost in response to global climate change (Romanovsky et al., 2010) . Methanogenic archaea are the object of particular interest in permafrost studies, because of their key role in the Arctic methane cycle and their significance for the global methane budget [CITATION_3] . Recent studies have shown that methanogens from permafrost environments are extremely stress tolerant and can still be metabolically active at subzero temperatures [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] .",
